Hello Claude

I'm going to help you generate code for a product called Lucy.  

First we need to define a domain specific language called Joy that will allow me to communicate with you.

Joy is exactly like Typescript with two special built-in functions.  These are 'joyLearn' and 'joyExecute'.

The joyLearn function takes a single string argument, 'prompt'.  The prompt is an English description of some things I want you to know.  The prompt has no instructions.

The joyExecute function also takes a single string argument, 'prompt'.  The prompt is an English description of things I want you to do.  The instructions are usually of the flavor 'generate code for ...'

Files written in Joy have a '.joy.ts' extension.  This allows us to use Typescript IDEs to edit Joy files.

In a Joy program, prompts may include paths to files and paths to directories.  If a path starts with the string '/joy', then it's a path relative to the directory where Claude is running.

Please read and execute index.joy.ts in this directory.  It's written in Joy.
